  "concubinageChecklist1Title": "Draft a will",
  "concubinageChecklist1Desc": "Without a will, your partner inherits nothing — everything goes to your parents or siblings. A handwritten will (handwritten, dated, signed) is sufficient. You can bequeath the disposable portion to your partner.",
  "concubinageChecklist2Title": "LPP beneficiary clause",
  "concubinageChecklist2Desc": "Contact your pension fund to register your partner as beneficiary. Without this clause, the LPP death capital does not go to them. Most funds accept the cohabitant under conditions (shared household, etc.).",
  "concubinageChecklist3Title": "Cohabitation agreement",
  "concubinageChecklist3Desc": "A written contract that governs the sharing of expenses, property ownership, and what happens in case of separation. Not mandatory, but strongly recommended — especially if you buy property together.",
  "concubinageChecklist4Title": "Cross life insurance",
  "concubinageChecklist4Desc": "A life insurance where each partner is the other's beneficiary compensates for the absence of AVS/LPP survivor's pension. Compare offers — premiums depend on age and insured capital.",
  "concubinageChecklist5Title": "Advance directive for incapacity",
  "concubinageChecklist5Desc": "If you become incapacitated (accident, illness), your partner has no power of representation. An advance directive for incapacity (CC art. 360 ff.) grants them this right.",
  "concubinageChecklist6Title": "Advance directives",
  "concubinageChecklist6Desc": "A document specifying your medical wishes in case of incapacity. You can designate your partner as the trusted person for medical decisions (CC art. 370 ff.).",
  "concubinageChecklist7Title": "Joint account for shared expenses",
  "concubinageChecklist7Desc": "A joint account simplifies managing shared expenses (rent, groceries, bills). Clearly define each person's contribution. In case of separation, the balance is split 50/50 unless agreed otherwise.",
  "concubinageChecklist8Title": "Joint or individual lease",
  "concubinageChecklist8Desc": "If you are on the lease with your partner, you are jointly liable. In case of separation, both must give notice. If only one is the leaseholder, the other has no rights to the housing.",
